Notebook[{
Cell[TextData["A Tutorial Introduction to the Quantum`Psi` Package"], "Title",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["by Alvin Goh"], "Subtitle",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"This package contains various functions for interacting with the PsiEv \
(Psi-Evolver) external program which, given an initial solution and a \
time-independent potential function, numerically integrates the \
one-dimensional Schrodinger equation to produce the solution for future \
times."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The boundary conditions used by PsiEv are that the wavefunction must be zero \
at x <= 0 and x >= w where w = 1 by default. (Units are chosen such that hbar \
= 1 and mass = 0.5.) In practice, this means that PsiEv simulates the \
evolution of the solution to the one-dimensional infinite square-well \
potential of width w. All experiments simulated with PsiEv must be such that \
they will fit within the confines of the well."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Loading the package"], "Section",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Let's load Quantum`Psi`!"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(<< "\<qpsi07.m\>"\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["We'll check out what's available with"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(?Quantum`Psi`*\)\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"You should see a list of symbols from AnimatePsi to XBoundaries which have \
been defined by this package. If not, stay cool! Try the commands again and \
if they still don't work then 'Houston, we have a problem' (Jim Lovell, Cmdr \
Apollo 13) - call Mission Control (a demonstrator)."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"We can see the current state of the quantum mechanical system simulated by \
PsiEv by (remember to try ?ShowCurrentState[])"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(ShowCurrentState[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"This shows the current simulation time at the top of the frame and the left, \
bottom and right sides of the infinite square well. Because no potential or \
wavefunction has been set as yet, these are still both zero and are not seen. \
The units of length and time are such that Planck's constant/(2Pi), hbar = 1 \
and mass, m = 1/2. No facility exists for changing these built-in values."], 
  "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Don't forget to delete graphics which are no longer needed to conserve \
memory. You may wish to delete the above graphic before moving on."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Hands-on demonstrations"], "Section",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"\"It's not enough just to stand and stare...\"\n\t\t\t\t\tPink Floyd\n\t\t\t\
\t\t\"On the turning away\""], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True,
  FontSize->10],

Cell[TextData[
"The best way to come to grips with the features of Quantum`Psi` is to try it \
out. To this end, we'll do a series of simulated experiments. These will only \
cover the most frequently used functions."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Free-particle wavepacket"], "Subsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["The Setup"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Let's set up a Gaussian wavepacket centred at a location a little over 1/2 \
of the way across the well, x=0.6. We must choose the standard deviation of x \
so that the wavefunction falls off to a low value which is effectively zero \
at the walls where x=0 and x=1. A value of 0.05 will suffice since it puts \
the closest wall (at x=1) 8 standard deviations away from the centre of the \
Gaussian curve. We'll also have to choose a mean momentum for the wavepacket; \
let's pick 100."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Note: Do not set up wavepackets with momenta much greater than 100 - because \
of limitations of the simulation, these may not be accurately modelled and \
appear to behave in a bizarre manner."], "SmallText",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The easiest way to set up a Gaussian wavepacket in PsiEv is to call \
SetGaussian. Hence, (use ?SetGaussian to find out more) we invoke"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(SetGaussian[0.6, 0.05, 100]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"SetGaussian returns the list of the values of the wavefunction which are \
kept by PsiEv. This list is rather long so in future, we'll use a semi-colon \
; at the end of the function call to suppress this result. Try this out by \
going back to the last command and adding a semicolon to the end and entering \
it again."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The potential will be set to zero to simulate a free particle. (Actually, of \
course, it's already zero because we haven't set it yet but let's just reset \
it for practice.)"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(SetSquarePotential[{0}]; \)\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Note the semicolon at the end; SetSquarePotential returns an unwieldy list \
of the potential function's values as kept by PsiEv."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"While we're at it, let's set the simulation time to zero. (Yes I know it's \
already zero but let's just do it for practice.)"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(SetTime[0]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Let's see what the setup is now."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(ShowCurrentState[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"You should see a graph of the absolute-square values of the wavefunction in \
the form of the well-known bell-shaped curve centred at x=0.25 (check the \
coordinates of the maximum point of the curve by selecting the graphic, \
enlarging it by dragging the handles and then holding down the Command key as \
you position the cursor over the point.)."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Running the simulation"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Now let's animate the wavefunction! To do this, use the AnimatePsi function. \
We'll produce a series of frames for times t=0 to t=0.001 by increments of \
0.0002. (Be careful not to set the time increment too large as it will then \
take a long time for PsiEv to produce a result.)"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(AnimatePsi[0.001, 0.0002]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"You should see that the Gaussian curve has moved to the right by an amount \
100/(1/2)*0.001=0.2 where 100 is the momentum, 1/2 is the mass and 0.001 is \
the time-interval."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Actually, things are starting to get interesting since the wavepacket is \
about to collide with the right wall of the well. Let's continue the \
simulation and see what happens."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(AnimatePsi[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Well! Let's see some more!"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(AnimatePsi[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"That was reflection of a Gaussian wavepacket off an infinite potential step! \
You can continue this simulation further if you like and confirm that the \
reflected wavepacket now travels with velocity v = -0.2, but don't forget to \
delete unneeded graphics when you're through."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Exercise"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[
"Set up a Gaussian wavepacket with mean momentum 50 and confirm that it's \
group velocity agrees with expectations."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Answer"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(SetTime[0]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetGaussian[0.25, 0.05, 50]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetSquarePotential[{0}]; \)\), 
    \(AnimatePsi[0.001, 0.0001]\)}], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Scattering from a potential step"], "Subsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["The Setup"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"We'll set up an experiment in which a Gaussian wavepacket will be scattered \
off a potential step. Let's choose the wavepacket to represent a particle at \
x = 0.25 with std. dev. of x of 0.05 and mean momentum 100. We'll have a step \
potential of height equal to 90% of the mean energy of the particle, i.e. 0.9 \
of 100^2/(2*0.5) = 0.9*10000 = 9000 where 100 is the particle's momentum and \
0.5 is the mass. Finally, we will reset the simulation clock to zero for the \
initial state."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(SetGaussian[0.25, 0.05, 100]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetSquarePotential[{0, 0.5, 9000}]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetTime[0]; \)\), 
    \(ShowCurrentState[Energy \[Rule] 100\^2, DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True]\)}],
   "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The Energy option allows specification of an arbitrary energy level which \
will be plotted to the same scale as the potential so as to allow easy \
comparison. The DisplayEnergy option controls the display of this energy \
plot. By default, the energy is plotted as a dashed cyan line. We will use \
this feature to display the mean energy of the wavepacket so it can be easily \
compared with the potential."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The graphic shows the potential function in green. It's height has been \
automatically scaled so that it spans the vertical range of the displayed \
graphic - it should not be inferred that the heights of the peak of the \
wavepacket and the potential function are in any way comparable. After all, \
they don't even have the same units!"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Incidentally, the default settings of the major options recognized by many \
of the functions of Quantum`Psi` can be seen using"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(Options[QuantumPsi]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["The Experimental Run"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Before we actually run the simulation, we should decide on what data to \
record."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"An important option for AnimatePsi is XBoundaries. This allows you to \
specify ranges of x of particular interest. AnimatePsi will then calculate \
the probability that the particle is in each of these ranges at each \
time-increment and save the results for later analysis. We are interested in \
the probabilities that the particle is to the left and to the right of the \
potential step so we'll use this option in our animation, specifying x-ranges \
of 0 to 0.5 to 1."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["After all that preparation, now it's all systems go!"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(AnimatePsi[0.005, 0.0002, Energy \[Rule] 10000, 
      DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True, XBoundaries \[Rule] {0, 0.5, 1}]\)], "Input",\

  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Data Analysis"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"We can examine the probabilities saved by our use of XBoundaries with"], 
  "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(ShowProbabilities[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The first graph labelled P[0<x<0.5] shows the probability that the particle \
is to be found between x=0 and x=0.5 while the second graph does the same for \
x=0.5 and x=1. The last graph shows both superimposed. The reflection and \
transmission coefficients can be read off these graphs as the value of \
P[0<x<0.5] and P[0.5<x<1] when the scattering event has completed but before \
the reflected waves reach the step. (Do it!) This can be checked against a \
theoretically derived value."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(N[RStep[Gaussian, 100, 10, 9000]]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"RStep is a function which returns the reflection coefficient for scattering \
from a potential step. It's second argument is the standard deviation in \
momentum. For a Gaussian at t=0, it is given by (hbar/2)/sigmax so in this \
case, its (1/2)/0.05 = 10. (You may see warning messages about underflows \
when using RStep but don't worry, be happy - they do not significantly alter \
the result for the cases you are likely to encounter.)"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Exercise"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[
"Repeat the above and run a simulation to 'experimentally' determine the \
transmission coefficient for a similar particle scattering off a potential \
step of height 10500 and check against predictions."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Answer"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(SetGaussian[0.25, 0.05, 100]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetSquarePotential[{0, 0.5, 10500}]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetTime[0]; \)\), 
    \(\(AnimatePsi[0.005, 0.0001, Energy \[Rule] 10000, 
      DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True, XBoundaries \[Rule] {0, 0.5, 1}]; \)\), 
    \(\(ShowProbabilities[]; \)\), 
    \(N[RStep[Gaussian, 100, 10, 10500]]\)}], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Tunnelling"], "Subsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Briefing"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"This experiment is almost identical to the step-scattering one except for \
the form of the potential which is a barrier potential. One can easily be set \
up."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Pre-flight check"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"We'll throw the Gaussian wavepacket we've used previously against a barrier \
potential of height 15000 and width 0.01 centred in the well. Hence, the \
potential will be set to zero for x from 0 to 0.5-0.01/2=0.495, to 15000 for \
x from 0.495 to 0.5+0.01/2=0.505, and 0 again for x from 0.505 to 1."], "Text",\

  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(SetSquarePotential[{0, 0.495, 15000, 0.505, 0}]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetGaussian[0.25, 0.05, 100]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetTime[0]; \)\), 
    \(ShowCurrentState[Energy \[Rule] 100\^2, DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True]\)}],
   "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The potential barrier may look more spiky than squarish - this is because it \
is too narrow to be displayed properly. Setting an option called JM to a \
value higher than its default can alleviate this problem but because this \
will increase memory demands and reduce speed, this is rarely worth doing. \
For practice, add JM->500 to ShowCurrentState above and see the difference."],
   "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Flight"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The data we'll be interested in collecting relate to the reflection and \
transmission coefficients for the particle scattering off the barrier. Hence, \
we'll be interested in the probability that the particle is to the left and \
to the right of the barrier, i.e. P[0 < x < 0.495] and P[0.505 < x < 1]. To \
keep this data, we must set the XBoundaries option appropriately."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Let's run the experiment!"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(AnimatePsi[0.003, 0.0001, Energy \[Rule] 100\^2, 
      DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True, XBoundaries \[Rule] {0, .495, .505, 1}]\)], 
  "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Now, wasn't that spectacular? Select the graphics and animate them to watch \
it again."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Debriefing"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Now for the exciting(?) part - let's examine that probability data we so \
painstakingly collected!"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(ShowProbabilities[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The graphs show what their labels say they show and the first and third \
graphs are the ones of interest to us. Read off the value for P[0 < x < \
0.495] when the tunneling event is over and compare it to predictions:"], 
  "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(N[RBarrier[Gaussian, 100, 10, 15000, 0.01]]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Exercise"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[
"Throw our Gaussian wavepacket against a barrier of height 9000 and width \
0.02 and check observed R against prediction."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Answer"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(SetTime[0]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetGaussian[0.25, 0.05, 100]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetSquarePotential[{0, 0.5 - 0.02\/2, 9000, 0.5 + 0.02\/2, 0}]; \)\), 
  
    \(\(AnimatePsi[0.003, 0.0002, Energy \[Rule] 100\^2, 
      DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True, 
      XBoundaries \[Rule] {0, 0.5 - 0.02\/2, 0.5 + 0.02\/2, 1}]; \)\), 
    \(\(ShowProbabilities[]; \)\), 
    \(N[RBarrier[Gaussian, 100, 10, 9000, 0.02]]\)}], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Harmonic Oscillator"], "Subsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Start"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Here's one of my favorites! We're going to simulate a system representing a \
particle subject to a restoring force of F = -k (x-x0) where x0 is the \
equilibrium position. The potential function is V = k (x-x0)^2 / 2 and we'll \
use a special function to set this so that the equilibrium position is \
centred in the well and we'll arbitrarily choose k = 250000 . Initially, \
we'll have the particle represented by our familiar Gaussian wavepacket \
centred in the well."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(SetTime[0]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetGaussian[0.5, 0.05, 100]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetHarmOscPotential[0.5, 250000]; \)\), 
    \(ShowCurrentState[Energy \[Rule] 100\^2, DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True]\)}],
   "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Middle"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Because of the behaviour of the wavepacket, it's advisable to increase the \
vertical range for this experiment. Trial and error shows that PlotMax->15 \
gives good results."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Data collection in this experiment will focus on whether the particle is in \
the left or right halves of the well so XBoundaries will be set \
appropriately."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(AnimatePsi[0.01, 0.0005, Energy \[Rule] 100\^2, 
      DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True, PlotMax \[Rule] 15, 
      XBoundaries \[Rule] {0, 0.5, 1}]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Finish"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Let's examine the collected data."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(ShowProbabilities[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The graphs show a little over one cycle of an oscillation and the period of \
the oscillation can be read off and compared to theory:"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(N[PeriodSHO[0.5, 250000]]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Exercise"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[
"Repeat the experiment with k=200000. Then change the momentum used in your \
answer to 50 and compare the periods."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["Answer"], "Subsubsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Since 2 values of momentum will be used, we'll first define a variable \
called momentum and use it in the code."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(momentum = 100; \)\), 
    \(\(SetTime[0]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetGaussian[0.5, 0.05, momentum]; \)\), 
    \(\(SetHarmOscPotential[0.5, 500000]; \)\), 
    \(\(AnimatePsi[0.007, 0.001, Energy \[Rule] momentum\^2, 
      DisplayEnergy \[Rule] True, XBoundaries \[Rule] {0, 0.5, 1}]; \)\), 
    \(\(ShowProbabilities[]; \)\), 
    \(N[PeriodSHO[0.5, 500000]]\)}], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"After running the above, just edit the first line to read momentum=50; and \
enter it again! This way you don't have to change every occurrence."], "Text",\

  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]],

Cell[TextData[
"This completes the coverage of the basics of Quantum`Psi` except for one, \
very, VERY IMPORTANT point. When you are through with using PsiEv (e.g. you \
wanna quit Mathematica) you MUST call the Quantum`Psi` function"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(Done[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"This will free the memory used by PsiEv but does not unload it. (For techies \
only: it ensures graceful termination by first freeing memory blocks \
previously allocated by calloc.) If you change your mind and want to use \
PsiEv again, just call"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(Init[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["and PsiEv will once again be at your beck-and-call."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Advanced topics"], "Section",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Reinitializing PsiEv"], "Subsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"It may become desirable to reset PsiEv to its initial state. This is easily \
done with"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(Init[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Entering an arbitrary wavefunction"], "Subsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"PsiEv is flexible and may be initialized with an arbitrary wavefunction. Due \
to technical difficulties, this must be done separately for the real and \
imaginary parts. Suppose the wavefunction Sin[Pi x] is required. The real \
part can be set by"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(SetPsiReal[Table[N[Sin[\[Pi]\ x]], {x, 0, 1, 0.001}]]; \)\)], "Input",\

  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"(Note the use of the N function - SetPsiReal only accepts lists of reals.) \
This will set up PsiEv's internal representation of the wavefunction by \
interpolating as necessary between the values in the list which has been \
passed to it. Best results are obtained when the length of the passed list is \
comparable to the size of PsiEv's internal array (determined by the first \
element of the list returned by GetParms[])."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["The imaginary part can be set uniformly to zero with"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(SetPsiImag[{0}]; \)\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData["The wavefunction can now be normalized by"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(NormalizePsi[]; \)\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Entering an arbitary potential function"], "Subsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"In a similar manner to the above section, an arbitrary potential function \
can be set. For example, let's set up a potential of the form V[x]=0 for \
0<=x<=0.5 and V[x]=x-0.5 for 0.5<x<=1. We can exploit PsiEv's interpolating \
behaviour so that we need only specify a three-element list."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(SetPotential[{0, 0, 0.5}]; \)\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"A more complicated potential function must be represented by a longer list, \
e.g."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(SetPotential[Table[N[Exp[x]], {x, 0, 1, 0.001}]]; \)\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData["Changing PsiEv's parameters"], "Subsection",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"PsiEv uses parameters which control the width of the potential well, the \
relation between the time-increment and x-increment and the number of points \
it uses internally to represent the wavefunction and potential function. \
These parameters can be changed, e.g. suppose we want a well of width 2 and \
2001 points to be used to represent the wavefunction and potential."], "Text",\

  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(SetParms[2001, 1, 2, 0]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The second parameter of SetParms is 2 epsilon^2/delta where epsilon and \
delta are the x- and t-increment respectively. It is usually best just to \
leave it as 1."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"Warning: Do not change these parameters willy-nilly! They have strong \
effects on the accuracy of the solutions generated."], "SmallText",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"The current settings of these parameters can be seen with"], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(GetParms[]\)], "Input",
  AspectRatioFixed->True],

Cell[TextData[
"These parameters are easily reset to their default values by reinitializing \
PsiEv (see above)."], "Text",
  Evaluatable->False,
  AspectRatioFixed->True]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]]
},
